Frequently Asked Questions
Updated March 29- 30, April 1, 3, 9, 13, 17, 21 2020

The district is closed through May 1, 2020, following Governor Bakerâ€™s directive. All school-related activities are also canceled.

Update: On April 21, Governor Baker announced schools are closed through the end of the 2019-20 school year.

The information detailed in this document is intended to provide guidance for this period. It is important to note that this is a fluid situation and so this document will be regularly updated and modified and it is recommended that you revisit frequently for the latest updates and information. 




Click on the link below for the questions specific to:

Student Learning

Frequently Asked Questions

Student Learning

Q.
My child is on an IEP. Will my child receive services during the closure?
A.
On March 21, 2020, the US Department of Education released a Supplemental Fact Sheet stating that during this national emergency â€œschool districts must provide a free and appropriate public education (FAPE) consistent with the need to protect the health and safety of students with disabilities and those individuals providing education, specialized instruction, and related services to these students.â€ Since this time, the MA Department of Elementary and Secondary Education has updated its guidance specific to the implementation of special education services during this period of school closure, urging all districts to â€œto use creative strategies to provide special education instruction and services to the extent feasible,â€ while recognizing that not all services can be delivered remotely. Special education teams have been connecting with families during these first two weeks of school closure to offer suggested strategies, troubleshoot challenges, and to provide accommodations or modifications to the enrichment activities. Expect this outreach to continue as teams and providers begin to shift to a more direct model of service delivery in the following weeks. 

For additional information, see the Special Education page on the districtâ€™s website.
Q.
Are the days during the closure counted as â€œschool days?â€
A. 
No. These are non-school days. These days will essentially be considered a seven week school closing period (March 13 - June 19). There is no expectation of online learning or for the provision of educational services during this period. However, the District has provided enrichment and practice resources to students and families by grade-level for each discipline that will be updated regularly. (https://arlingtonenrich.wixsite.com/mysite) It is important to note that the school year ends June 19th.
Q. 
Are there expectations around Remote Learning for Students or Teachers?
A. 
Arlington Public Schools has released a Remote Learning Plan for April 6 - May 4. It updates the information shared earlier (below). This marks a transition to providing more structured activities and activities for students. The plan provides background information, and details for each school level. Please see the document for more information regarding your childâ€™s level in school.

Prior to April 6, the district shared this information, which may still be useful:
Starting the week of March 30, you should expect your student(s) to have contact with teachers twice during the week. At the elementary level, contact will come from teachers to parents/guardians, and at the secondary level, teachers will contact students through Google Classroom. 
We plan for remote learning to include both online computer-based, and offline learning activities. Students at all levels will be sent learning activity assignments. These assignments and other learning activities should engage students for three (3) hours a day, three and a half hours (3-Â½) for high school students. The Enrichment Activities for Students page on the district website https://arlingtonenrich.wixsite.com/mysite/updates , which was developed by APS teachers, coaches, and administrators, is a continually updated resource of learning activities for students at all levels.
On March 26, the Massachusetts Department of Elementary and Secondary Education released recommendations for remote learning on its COVID-19 updates page. 
Some additional information: 
At the elementary level, grade 3-5 parents/guardians will be given instructions to assist their student to log into Google Classroom so that students in those grades can begin using Google Classroom beginning the week of April 6 to communicate with their teacher. Students who have been using Google Classroom this year can continue to log into Google Classroom next week. Otherwise, assigned learning activities will be sent to parentsâ€™ email.
At the secondary level, students should expect to see a learning activity assignment from each of their classes in Google Classroom. Teachers will be giving students feedback on their work. Assignments will not be graded, but are expected to be completed. 
Students can choose when during the day to do their work, but it is suggested that a schedule be developed that works for your family. Click on the following link to view a sample schedule that can assist with organizing your childâ€™s learning time for the day: Sample Student Schedule.Some messages from teachers to parents may include short videos to share with your child.  Other online resources: https://arlingtonenrich.wixsite.com/mysite/updates

Q.
What do I need to know about Google Classroom?
A.
Google Classroom is a learning management platform that teachers and students use to access learning activities. Teachers create an online classroom, invite students, and then distribute assignments through their Classroom. Students sign into their Google Classroom with their Spyponders accounts. Step by step instructions on logging in from home and joining a Classroom can be found in this Google Slideshow called Spyponders Sign-in from Home. Information about Spyponders usernames and initial passwords can be found in the For Families: Spyponders Account Login Information doc. Instructions will be provided to parents/guardians on the district website as well as emailed to K-2 parents. If families need a password reset or have another issue related to their childâ€™s Spyponders accounts, they can notify the Digital Learning Department by completing the Spyponders Password Reset form. 
Q.
What resources are available for teachers, parents, and students to enrich learning during this period of closure?
A.
The district is providing Enrichment Activities for Students on the district website.

These resources and links are deemed suitable no matter the nature or pathway their teacher has provided. Suggestions about time on task for each level are also provided.
Q.
How can parents/students effectively use the enrichment activities posted on the Arlington Public Schools website? 
A.
Since the purpose of the enrichment activities is not to recreate the school day, parents and students can choose the activity and the duration for the activity, based upon interest and/or need. The recommendation is to spend 15-30 minutes per content area each day. Thus, parents/students can choose from a list of activities to complete in one day for each content area. The most important goal is for the family to create together a realistic daily schedule that can assist with providing structure for students while they are out of school. The schedule can be adjusted as family needs and daily home activities and responsibilities may change due to unforeseen circumstances. A daily schedule will help to keep students regulated and focused on developing the skills that they have learned in school to date. Once a schedule is established, the activities from the Enrichment Activities for Students page can be used to populate the schedule. Parents/students can also pull from other suggested activities found under the â€œonline resourcesâ€ tab and the â€œsupplemental resourcesâ€ tab. Finally, please remember to integrate academic tasks with fun and engaging activities that will help to meet studentsâ€™ social and emotional needs and the need for physical activity. 
Q.
How can I help my elementary student log into their Spyponders Google Drive account?
A.
Instructions for helping elementary students to log into their Spyponders Google Drive account are found on the Elementary Spyponders Info Sheet 2019 - 2020.
Q.
Given this closure, what happens with the MCAS testing?
A.
Commissioner Riley announced that with MAâ€™s federal testing waiver secured and the state legislation officially enacted, he is officially announcing that this spring's MCAS in grades 3-10 is cancelled this year.
Q.
What if I am scheduled to take the SAT and the school/testing center is closed?
A.
The College Board has posted information on its website about changes in the SAT testing process. The School Counseling Department shared this information on April 1:

Both the March and May SAT exams have been cancelled. The June 6th exam is still scheduled to take place as of now at Arlington High School. Please register early so you are guaranteed space. August is another option, but unfortunately AHS is not a testing site for the August exam. Register early so that you can have a location close to Arlington. Collegeboard is exploring additional test dates and/or testing options for students as well. Please visit this webpage for continued updates regarding the SAT and SAT Subject Tests. **Many colleges have also changed their SAT requirements for 2020-2021. Please check individual college websites for their SAT testing requirements.**
Q. 
What if I am scheduled to take the ACT and the school/testing center is closed?

The April 4th exam has been postponed to June 13th. All students who had previously registered for the April exam will receive an email from ACT instructing them on how they can reschedule their exam to June or a future date at no cost. Please visit this webpage for continued updates.
Q.
How will Advanced Placement exams be given during the closure? 
A.
Due to social distancing, the College Board has postponed the Advanced Placement Exams (AP) and is going to issue a modified exam. The exam will be administered remotely (online), take 45 minutes, and have reduced content. Given that not all families have equal access to a good testing environment and that access to the AP content has been interrupted, we will waive the requirement that students in AP courses take the AP exam. We believe it is in the best interest of students to take the AP, but will not require participation. 

For information on scheduling and refunds at AHS, please check this AP Cancellations Policies & Procedures. 

 Resources from the College Board can be found HERE. 
Q.
Is the AHS Spring College Fair happening?

The AHS SPRING COLLEGE FAIR is canceled. 
Please feel free to reach out to any colleges with your questions. They are here for you during these closures. Many colleges offer virtual tours and admissions offices across the country are working on creating more robust virtual information sessions in an effort to connect with prospective students. Here is a list of virtual college tours for the 30 most popular colleges where AHS students apply. Donâ€™t forget, Naviance is a great place to research colleges as well! Viewing College Profiles.

Frequently Asked Questions
Special Education

Q.
Is there a way for families of students with special needs to find resources and supports tailored to these particular needs?
A.
The MA Department of Elementary and Secondary Education has released a COVID-19 Family Letter & Family Resource Toolbox that provides links to a wide range of resources including state resources, family supports, hotlines, assistive technology, caregiver tools, and more.
Q.
My child is on an IEP, and I am concerned about the implications of the closure on my childâ€™s educational progress.
A.
Upon the conclusion of the closure, and the re-opening of the district, IEP teams will be available to convene to determine what type of impact the closure had on your childâ€™s educational progress, and make an individualized team-based decision as needed. Please refer to the following guidance.
Q.
My child is on an IEP and attends an out of district placement. What are the implications of Arlingtonâ€™s closure on my child attending the out of district placement?
A.
Arlingtonâ€™s closure should not have any impact on your child attending the out-of-district placement, as long as the program stays open. As information is changing daily, please communicate directly with the outplacement school for any updates on their closures. As of this correspondence, our transportation providers have confirmed they will continue to transport our students to outplacements that remain open. 
Q.
My child is on an IEP. Will my child receive services during the closure?
A.
On March 21, 2020, the US Department of Education released a Supplemental Fact Sheet stating that during this national emergency â€œschool districts must provide a free and appropriate public education (FAPE) consistent with the need to protect the health and safety of students with disabilities and those individuals providing education, specialized instruction, and related services to these students.â€ Since this time, the MA Department of Elementary and Secondary Education has updated its guidance specific to the implementation of special education services during this period of school closure, urging all districts to â€œto use creative strategies to provide special education instruction and services to the extent feasible,â€ while recognizing that not all services can be delivered remotely. Special education teams have been connecting with families during these first two weeks of school closure to offer suggested strategies, troubleshoot challenges, and to provide accommodations or modifications to the enrichment activities. Expect this outreach to continue as teams and providers begin to shift to a more direct model of service delivery in the following weeks. 

For additional information, see the Special Education page on the districtâ€™s website.
Q.
Will my childâ€™s special education liaison, related service provider, and elementary/secondary coordinators be available if I have a question during this closure?
A.
Yes, special education teachers, related services providers, elementary/secondary coordinators, as well as the Director of Special Education will be available to assist with specific questions as needed. You can expect a â€œcheck-insâ€ from your childâ€™s liaison, in the form of a phone call or email at least twice weekly during this time as well. 
Q.
Will IEP Team meetings take place during school closure?
A.
Yes, the Arlington Public Schools District is committed to offering remote special education Team meetings telephonically and virtually so that the IEP Team process may continue. For additional details, please see the district update on this topic and your building special education team chairperson will be in contact with you during the next two weeks to begin scheduling.
Q.
I have made a request of the district for an Independent Evaluation at public expense on or after March 13th. What should I expect?
A.
Any timelines associated with an independent evaluation request received on March 13th or during the closure will be processed using day one of the timeline as the date the district re-opens. For example, if the district re-opens on May 4th, that would count as day one associated with timelines for an independent evaluation request.
Q.
I am looking for general tips on how to support my child during this closure.
A.
Arlington Public Schools is providing enrichment activities for students on the district website. Information on supporting mental health and well-being during school closure is also on the website. The Massachusetts Department of Elementary and Secondary Education has also provided resources for parents http://www.doe.mass.edu/highstandards/. Your childâ€™s special education liaison and/or service provider will be contacting you to answer questions and give suggestions on how to customize these activities for your individual child. 

DESE and WGBH Partnership for Educational Resources
PBS LearningMedia, https://mass.pbslearningmedia.org/, and WGBHâ€™s new online Distance Learning Center, https://www.wgbh.org/distance-learning-center
The Department is partnering with WGBH to bring educational resources to students and families through television and digital media. WGBH has created a distance learning site with the hope to reach as many students and caregivers as possible. PBS LearningMedia is a FREE digital repository of tens of thousands of high-quality media resources that are contextualized for educational use. The resources span disciplines for grades PreK-12, are aligned to national and state standards, and include videos, comprehensive lessons, interactive activities, and support materials (teaching tips, background readings, and student handouts).

Frequently Asked Questions
Activities, Events, and Athletics

Q.
Are there any athletic, club, or activity events happening during this period of closure?
A.
No. All school-related events are canceled during this period.
Q.
Will there be a Spring Sports Season?
A.
The MIAA Board of Directors voted that if we are back in school on May 4th we will have a Spring Sports Season. During this fluid situation the BOD will continue to meet and give updates on the Spring Season. The MIAA will follow the expectations and orders put forth by Governor Baker in relation to COVID-19. 
Q.
What can student athletes do to prepare for the spring season?
A.
No students should be in the building, gyms, or weight room at Arlington High School until we return to school. We recommend that students work out on their own during this time period and encourage students not to gather in big groups. 
Q.
Where can I find updates about Arlington Athletics and updates from the MIAA?
A.
Updates from the MIAA and Arlington Athletics can be found on our athletic blog link below. https://sites.google.com/arlington.k12.ma.us/athletics/home
Q.
Can students register for spring sports while the schools are closed?
A.
Yes, registration for spring sports can still be done online. Here is the link to register https://hello.familyid.com/. If you have any questions please email the Athletic Director at jbowler@arlington.k12.ma.us.
Q.
Are All Town Chorus, All Town Band, AHS Musical and the PreK-12 Art Show canceled?
A.
These events are canceled.
Q.
How will the delays and cancellations impact stipends and payments for coaches and advisors?
A.
For activities and athletic events/seasons, we will need to revisit what and how those earning stipends will be paid. More information will be forthcoming following further discussions.

Return to top


Frequently Asked Questions
General Questions

Q.
How will the days of this school closure count against school days?
A.
Arlington will be in school through June 25, 2020, which is our regularly scheduled 185th day. This is the last day we will be accountable for in terms of the stateâ€™s mandated time on learning. However, as this unprecedented situation continues we will continue to have discussions with all stakeholders about what is in the best interest of students.
Q.
Currently, the schools are closed through May 1, 2020. Will this be extended? How will we be notified?
A.
Arlington Public Schools will continue to monitor this fluid situation and will make the best determinations in the best interest of the students and staff. Information will continue to be provided via School Messenger, on our website, and on all major news outlets.
Q.
What will happen to the April vacation (April 20-24)?
A.
At this time the April vacation week is scheduled as planned. However, given these unexpected school closures, we may revisit the need for additional school days and this will be revisited in the near future with all impacted employees.
Q.
How will the school community provide information on travel, health, and other important factors that will help us to determine our readiness to reopen?
A.
The district is currently working on a process to collect this information. All school trips scheduled for this spring and summer have been cancelled. Further information regarding the cancellations has been sent to participants on the trips.
Q.
How can I make sure I get all School Messenger emails that the district is sending to families?
A.
Be sure to confirm that your contact information (email & phone number) is current on the PowerSchool Parent portal. Access PowerSchool here: https://aps.powerschool.com/public/ and go to "Student Info' to check the information we have on file at your building. 

If changes are required, click on the 'School Information' icon directly above student info on the left side menu for who to contact at your child's school for these changes. 
Q.
Will food services be available for students that qualify for free and reduced lunch?
A.
Starting on Monday, March 30, school lunches will no longer be available for pick-up and the Arlington EATS Market will be temporarily closed to shoppers. This is to ensure the safety of all of our citizens. Instead, Arlington EATS and the Town of Arlington will be delivering shelf-stable food to any Arlington resident in need. To receive food:
Call Arlington Food Hotline at (781) 316-3400 or click here.
Please leave a message with your name, address, phone number, family size and you will receive a call back as soon as possible.
Deliveries will include canned and shelf-stable food and may include prepared meals.
Please call back when you need another delivery.
Q.
Where can families find additional food support at this time?

 Arlington EATS and the Town of Arlington will be delivering shelf-stable food to any Arlington resident in need. To receive food:
Call Arlington Food Hotline at (781) 316-3400 or click here.
Please leave a message with your name, address, phone number, family size and you will receive a call back as soon as possible.
Deliveries will include canned and shelf-stable food and may include prepared meals.
Please call back when you need another delivery.
Q.
My family lives in Boston. Where can I find school lunches and food support?
A.
Boston Public Schools is offering breakfast and lunch from 8:30 to 11:30. Families can find locations here. The City of Boston is also sharing a map of meal sites. Project Bread is also sharing school meals sites and other food information on its website. If you need additional food resources, you can contact Project Breadâ€™s Food Source Hotline at (800) 645-8333.


Q.
Should everyone be practicing social distancing?
A.
Yes. â€œNow, we ask that you do your part. Creating social gatherings during the school outage will minimize the impact of closing school. Carefully consider the necessity of being together. The Department of Elementary and Secondary Education writes:
During this period, it is critical that students and their families, as well as school staff, stay home as much as possible. If you leave your home, it is essential to strictly follow social distancing guidelines by avoiding crowds, canceling social gatherings, and maintaining a safe separation of at least 6 feet from others. Restricting access to school buildings will have little impact on public health if these best practices are not followed in good faith.

A. 
The Counseling Department of Arlington Public Schools is sharing information to support mental health and well-being during the COVID-19 school closure on a Mental Health and Well-Being during School Closure website. Here is this week's (4/13-4/17) schedule for live programming from the Mental Health and Well Being from this website.

There are additional Social Emotional Resources for Parents (Under Online Resources) on the Enrichment Activities for Students page. 
Q. 
How can I talk about the novel coronavirus with my child/ren?
A.
Principals have found this CDC resource to be helpful.

Also, the National Association of School Psychologists has advice on how to talk about the virus with children (https://www.nasponline.org/resources-and-publications/resources-and-podcasts/school-climatesafety-and-crisis/health-crisis-resources/talking-to-children-about-covid-19-%28coronavirus%29-aparent-resource).
Q.
What about using school or other playgrounds? What about playdates?
A.
As of March 19, ALL Town and School playgrounds, playscapes, swings, basketball and tennis courts, the skate park, and athletic fields are closed until further notice. Read the CDCs FAQ on COVID-19 and Children.
Q.
Are there any resources or social stories for children?
A.
The district is sharing enrichment activities for students on the APS website and several social stories can be found here.

A.

Website: http://arlingtonma.gov/health
Q.
Where should I go for updates from the Town of Arlington?
A.
